						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">hawken wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">apparently developers were asked not to use $30 because it caused problems with some CRT sets as it was &quot;whiter than white&quot; - indeed games would be rejected by Nintendo if they used #30.</div><br />Where did you get this information? I don't think I've ever heard this before...<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The same went for $0d as it was &quot;blacker than black&quot; (not sure what damage that could do though).</div><br />Blacker than black is a well known issue... It doesn't cause any actual damage, but some TV mistake this color for sync signals, distorting the picture or causing it to &quot;roll&quot;.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">$e &amp; $f range were not allowed either.</div><br />Again, never heard of this. $0f is widely used for black in homebrew games.</div>

